<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>04. Edward H. Bennett to Edward B. Butler, May 19, 1914.</strong><br />       Chicago, like all American cities, had no zoning regulations during the first part of the 20th century. Residential, commercial, and industrial buildings coexisted uneasily&#151;with houses, taverns, tanneries, and livery stables in close proximity or even on the same block&#151;and a disproportionate share of this burden was borne by the poorest neighborhoods. Legal recourses available to residents were limited to private-nuisance litigation, restrictive covenants, and frontage consents, the latter two of which were later struck down as being unconstitutional. Though New York City's landmark comprehensive zoning ordinance&#151;the nation's first&#151;was not adopted until 1916, groundwork for it was laid two years earlier. Though not a binding legal document, the <em>Plan</em> nevertheless bolstered the idea that the city needed to exert more control over land use while increasing awareness of the economic cost of continued inaction. Chicago’s first zoning ordinance was finally passed into law on March 12, 1923.<br /><br />
    	 "Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009," Case 1, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29–December 1, 2010<a href="http://digital-libraries.saic.edu/u?/mqc,8700">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
    </div><!--/artwork-details-->
